<title>FOAM Build</title>
<h1>Pom-O-Matic</h1>
<p>Solve your Build troubles with Pom-O-Matic!</p>

<h1>Overview</h1>

<p>The FOAM build is a <b>node</b> tool which executes Javascript methods (<b>Tasks</b>) against Project Object Model (<b>POM</b>)(or a more lighthearted acronym expansion: Pom-O-Matic) files.</p>

<p>The build manages three components: environment variables (envs), options, and tasks:
<ul>
  <li>envs - variables which can be set directly or via <i>options</i>, and impact the execution of <i>tasks</i>.</li>
  <li>options - provide build specific command line arguments. Options can manipulate <i>envs</i> and impact the execution of <i>tasks</i>.</li>
  <li>tasks - methods which act against the source code to generate an application. </li>
</ul>

<p><b>POMs</b> are JSON files which identify source code, application configuration, and build instructions. They are hierarchical and can exist at any level of a code repository.</p>

<p>Presently, there are two types of POMs, or more precisely, two types of POM <b>fields</b>
<ol>
  <li><b>Tooling</b> - fields which configure the Build environment itself with tasks and environment variables.
  <p>Fields which set up tasks and environment variables for the build.js process.  <i>For example</i>, <b>JavaTooling</b> adds variables to control the Java target version, adds command line arguments to control creating a JAR file or start the JVM with JDPA enabled, adds Tasks for building and starting from JAR file locally or building a TAR file for remote deployment.</p>
  </li>
  <li><b>Build</b> - fields which declare build inputs.
  <p>Such as code and deployment configuration to include.  <i>For example</i>, specifying the models to generate Java from and specifying the configuration to include in a JAR file.</p>
  </li>
</ol>
</p>

<p>There are three distinct build <b>phases</b>:
<ol>
  <li><b>Tooling</b> - the build loads Tooling POMs which add evironment variables (<b>envs</b>), command line options (<b>args</b>), and build <b>Tasks</b> specific to the type of code generation, compilation, and deployment to be supported.
  </li>
  <li><b>Environment and Registration</b> - the build processes the Build POMs to (1) set environment variable values for variables added during the Tooling phase (i.e., Java target release = 21), and (2) register Build POM <b>Tasks</b> to be run when same-named Tooling <b>Tasks</b> are run (i.e., <b>buildJavaOpts</b> JAVA_OPTS=-Dxyz before the JVM is started).
  </li>
  <li><b>Task</b> - the build processes the command line arguments, for options added during the Tooling phase, and prepares a set of <b>Tasks</b> which are then executed.  The <b>Tasks</b> themselves, act on the Build POMs.
  </li>
</ol>
</p>

<h1>Command Line Arguments</h1>
<p>Both single character (-h) and GNU getopt word style (--help) arguments are supported.<br/>
The GNU args can also be comma seperated <i>For example</i> --cleanAll,all
</p>

<p>A number of single character options, such as <b>N, O, P</b> are actually short cuts for setting evironment variables which can also be set via argument <b>E</b> which takes the full upper case environment variable name. <i>For example</i> -Nfoo or -EAPP_NAME:foo.
</p>

<p>build.js and the Tooling POMs define <b>options</b> and <b>tasks</b>, such as:</p>
<code>
foam.POM({
  options: {
    test: [ 't', 'test', 'TEST', 'Run All tests.', false, ...]
  },
  ...
  tasks: {
    runTests: ['Run all or specified test cases. ex: runTests[:Test1,Test2]', ['pomEnvs'], ...]
  }
})
</code>
Which can be invoked as
<code>
$ node foam3/tools/build.js -ct
# Or
$ node foam3/tools/build.js --clean --test --all
# Or
$ node foam3/tools/build.js --runTests
</code>

<h1>Help on Help</h1>
Build usage is generated by the <b>help</b> option and can be invoked in a number of ways:
<code>
$ node foam3/tools/build.js --help
$ node foam3/tools/build.js -h
$ node foam3/tools/build.js -?
</code>
<p>Help output is broken in three sections: options, tasks, environment variables (envs). Help can display just one of the sections by passing an argument to help.<br/>
For example, the following will only output the environment variables.
<code>$ node foam3/tools/build.js --help:envs</code>
</p>
<p>Help can also output the usage or information of a single option, task, or environment variable. <br/>
For example, the following will only output usage of <b>help</b> itself
<code>$node foam3/tools/build.js --help:help</code>
</p>

<h1>Troubleshooting</h1>
<p>Adding argument <b>--show-report</b> will cause the build to output the final value of all environment variables at the point of exit on error, or just before start CORE.</p>

<h1>POMs</h1>
<h2><i>Incomplete</i></h2>
<p>POMs are hierarchical and a POM is responsible for the files in it's directory and child directories which themselves do not contain a POM.</p>
<h2>POM structure</h2>
<h3>Build POMs</h3>
Fields:
<ul>
  <li>name - a non-unique identifier that distinguishes the POM in it's local scope. Used when reporting POM issues.
  <code>
  foam.POM({
    name: 'foam',
    ...
  </code>
  <p>Also used to set APP_NAME. A different APP_NAME can be specified in <b>envs:</b>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>exclude - directories under this POM which should not be processed if they do not contain a POM.</li>
  <li>envs - map of key-values pairs to set build environment variables or options.
  <code>
  foam.POM({
    name: 'foam-full',
    ...
    envs: {
      appName: 'foam'
    },
  </code>
  </li>
  <li>licenses - source code licenses which applies to the source managed by this POM. </li>
  <li>version - major[-minor-revision] string used to distinguish a build.
  <code>
  foam.POM({
    ...
    version: '1.0.0',
  </code>
  </li>
  <li>projects -  (and flags  -   test) </li>
  <li>files - </li>
  <li>javaFiles - </li>
  <li>journalFiles - </li>
  <li>flowDocFiles - (FUTURE) </li>
  <li>tasks - (project defined tasks)</li>
  <li>copy - (build provided tasks)</li>
  <li>Tooling specific - java, javaDependencies, javaFiles (above)</li>
</ul>

<h4>Creating a Build POM Tasks</h4>

<h3>Tooling POMs</h3>
Fields:
<ul>
  <li>name</li>
  <li>envs - Environment Variables
  <p>Environment variables are declared with default values in the Tooling POMs.  Build POMs and the CLI can set override or append to the environment variable values. <i>For example</i>, JAVA_OPTS, which controls the JVM environment, can be appended to with build specific parameters such as -Xmx  or -Dappproperty.</p>
  <code>
$ node tools/build.js -EJAVA_OPTS:"-Xms12g -Xmx12g"
  </code>
  </li>
  <li>options</li>
  <li>tasks</li>
</ul>

